## Component Extension

Components ship with exportable styling primitives so consumers can extend variants without forking source files.

### Adding a custom variant

Components with CVA variants export a `*Base` string and a `*VariantClasses` / `*StatusClasses` / `*SizeClasses` object. Spread these to build an extended CVA config:

```tsx
import { cva } from 'class-variance-authority'
import { statusBadgeBase, statusBadgeVariantClasses } from '@lizi-teo/ai-chat-ui/primitives'

const extendedVariants = cva(statusBadgeBase, {
  variants: {
    variant: {
      ...statusBadgeVariantClasses,
      vip: 'bg-[--vip]/10 text-[--vip]',        // ŌåÉ token class, not hardcoded colour
    },
  },
  defaultVariants: { variant: 'default' },
})
```

Then render with your own wrapper component that accepts the extended type.

**Rule: custom variants must use CSS custom properties.** Define `--vip` in your `.theme-{client}` class or `ThemeProvider` tokens. Never use `bg-yellow-400` or `#hex` directly.

### Overriding style with className

All primitives accept `className`. Use it with token-based Tailwind classes when a variant export isn't needed:

```tsx
<Tag label="Express" className="bg-primary/10 text-primary" />
```

### Extending sizes

`EntityAvatar` exports `entityAvatarSizeClasses`. Add extra sizes the same way:

```tsx
import { entityAvatarBase, entityAvatarSizeClasses } from '@lizi-teo/ai-chat-ui/primitives'

const myAvatarVariants = cva(entityAvatarBase, {
  variants: {
    size: { ...entityAvatarSizeClasses, xl: 'size-20 text-lg' },
  },
  defaultVariants: { size: 'md' },
})
```

### What belongs in the library vs your project

| Add to library | Keep in your project |
|---|---|
| Semantically universal variants (`neutral`, `pending`) | Brand-specific variants (`vip`, `loyalty`, `member-gold`) |
| New size tokens used by multiple tiers | One-off size overrides |
| Structural changes to a component | Cosmetic theme differences |

